<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900731-0045</DOCNO><DOCID>900731-0045.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- LTV Corp.:   Concern Reports Earnings   Rose Sharply in 2nd Period</HL><DATE>07/31/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><CO>   LTV</CO><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)EARNINGS (ERN)STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)</IN><LP>   LTV Corp., Dallas, said second-quarter net income morethan doubled because of a special gain this year and aspecial charge a year earlier.   Net rose to $76.6 million, or 59 cents a share, from $30.3million, or 21 cents a share, a year earlier. The 1990quarter reflected a gain of $44.3 million on the sale of astainless steel unit. The 1989 quarter was reduced by $80million in write-downs and charges on aircraft productionassets.</LP><TEXT>   Operating profit fell 64% to $36.6 million from $102.6million before charges a year earlier. Revenue fell 4.5% to$1.59 billion from $1.66 billion.   Steel operations contributed almost all of the decline inoperating profit. LTV, which is operating under protection ofbankruptcy law, attributed the decline to lower prices, lowersales and higher labor costs.   In the first half, profit rose to $120.8 million, or 91cents a share, from $106.9 million, or 82 cents a share, ayear earlier. Revenue fell 6% to $3.08 billion from $3.28billion.</TEXT></DOC>